The computational complexity assumption to find  the prime factors of a large number $N$ is the basis for the security of the ubiquitous RSA, a cornerstone of the public key cryptosystems so widely used in our digital society. e-commerce, SW distribution or the citizens' privacy is guarded by the difficulty of this problem alone. This makes very important the study of new factorization algorithms but,  fortunately and despite the many mathematical and computational advances, the factorization time  of the best classical algorithms still scales worse than polynomially  in the number of bits of $N$  \cite{sieves} meaning that, by now, the building blocks of the cyberinfrastructure are still solid.

The practical relevance of this assumption for the future has been recently highlighted by security agencies such as the NSA \cite{NSA_report} since,  in the quantum world, factoring is an easy problem that requires only polynomial resources when using Shor's algorithm \cite{shor}. Quantum measurement and entanglement, the property that gives to quantum systems access to an exponentially large Hilbert space, makes quantum computation different from classical computing and opens avenues for fundamentally new algorithms. 


However the reduction in complexity achieved by Shor's algorithm, when it comes to factor the numbers of the size used in real-world cryptosystems, is still far beyond what can be achieved with current technologies \cite{EnriqueMartinetal}. In this situation, we could  ask ourselves for the possibility to build the solutions in Hilbert space of a quantum simulator performing factorization instead of going through the route of a gate-based, fully programmable, quantum computer. The key idea is to translate factoring arithmetics into the  physics of a  device whose superposition of  states  mimics the problem i.e.: a factoring (analog) computer. The states of the simulator would be the solutions of some hermitian operator depending only on the number that we want to factorize. The output of a measurement 
will provide the probability for some $x$ to be a factor of $N$: arithmetic functions are thus transformed in physical observables.



Finding the prime factors of  $N$ is just equivalent to consider all possible prime numbers $x$ smaller than $\sqrt{N}$: $\pi(x)\leq \pi(\sqrt{N})=j$.
This simple, $x$ could be as well a factor of  all those $N_{k}$'s in a neighborhood $\mathcal{F}(j)=\{N_{k}$ / $\pi(N_{k}^{1/2})=j \}$.  We call $\mathcal{F}(j)$ the factorization ensemble of $N$, defining the proximity of $N$ that exhausts all the co-prime factor candidates $(x_k, y_k)$ of $N_{k}=x_k y_{k}$.

